# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cambridge-massachusetts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] In 1853 the country contains 89 telegraph lines that stretched 23,261 miles (37,435 km).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] When published in 1854, the country had an estimated 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Founded in December 1630 during the colonial era, Cambridge was one among the first cities established in the Thirteen Colonies, and it went on to play a historic role during the American Revolution.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In May 1775, approximately 16,000 American patriots assembled in Cambridge Common to begin organizing a military retaliation against British troops following the Battles of Lexington and Concord.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] On July 2, 1775, two weeks after the Second Continental Congress in Philadelphia formally established the Continental Army and appointed George Washington commander of it, Washington arrived at Cambridge Common to take command of the Patriot soldiers camped there.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Many of these soldiers played a role in supporting Washington's successful siege of Boston, which trapped garrisoned British troops from moving by land, forcing the British to ultimately abandon Boston.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge Common is thus celebrated as the birthplace of the Continental Army.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Harvard University, an Ivy League university founded in Cambridge in 1636, is the oldest institution of higher learning in the United States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), a private research university, has its 168-acre campus in Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Kendall Square, near MIT in the eastern part of Cambridge, has been called "the most innovative square mile on the planet" due to the high concentration of startup companies that have emerged there since 2010.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 2022, Cambridge was home to over 250 biotech companies, with more than 120 located within the Kendall Square ZIP Code.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Native Americans inhabited the Charles River basin for thousands of years prior to European colonization of the Americas, as confirmed by archaeological remains in neighboring Watertown and Boston.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] At the time of European contact, the area was inhabited by Naumkeag of the Pawtucket Confederacy to the north and Massachusett to the south.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The contact period introduced a number of European infectious diseases which would decimate native populations in virgin soil epidemics, significantly depopulating the Charles River basin upon the arrival of large groups of English settlers in the 1630s.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] A deed for the land that includes present-day Cambridge was ultimately obtained from the Naumkeag Squaw Sachem of Mistick in 1639, after a leptospirosis epidemic in 1616–1619 and a smallpox epidemic in 1633 killed large portions of her tribe, including two of her sons.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The first settlement of the Massachusetts Bay Colony was established in Salem, in June of 1626.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] That December, the site of present-day Cambridge was chosen for development because it was safely upriver from Boston Harbor, making it easily defensible from attacks by enemy ships.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city was founded by Thomas Dudley, his daughter Anne Bradstreet, and his son-in-law Simon Bradstreet.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The first houses were built in the spring of 1631.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The settlement was initially referred to as "the newe towne".
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Official Massachusetts records show the name rendered as **Newe Towne** by 1632, and as **Newtowne** by 1638.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Located at the first convenient Charles River crossing west of Boston, Newtowne was one of several towns, including Boston, Dorchester, Watertown, and Weymouth, founded by the 700 original Puritan colonists of the Massachusetts Bay Colony who arrived on the Winthrop Fleet.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Its first preacher was Thomas Hooker, who led many of its original inhabitants west in 1636 to found Hartford and the Connecticut Colony; before leaving, they sold their plots to more recent immigrants from England.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The original village site is now within Harvard Square.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The marketplace where farmers sold crops from surrounding towns at the edge of a salt marsh (since filled) remains within a small park at the corner of John F.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1636, Newe College, later renamed Harvard College after benefactor John Harvard, was founded as North America's first institution of higher learning.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Its initial purpose was training ministers.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] According to Cotton Mather, Newtowne was chosen for the site of the college by the Great and General Court, then the legislature of the Massachusetts Bay Colony, primarily for its proximity to the popular and highly respected Puritan preacher Thomas Shepard.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In May 1638, the settlement's name was changed to Cambridge in honor of the University of Cambridge in Cambridge, England.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1639, the Great and General Court purchased the land that became present-day Cambridge from the Naumkeag Squaw Sachem of Mistick.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the late 19th century, various schemes for annexing Cambridge to Boston were pursued and rejected.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Newtowne's ministers, Hooker and Shepard, the college's first president, the college's major benefactor, and the first schoolmaster Nathaniel Eaton were all Cambridge alumni, as was the colony's governor John Winthrop.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1629, Winthrop had led the signing of the founding document of the city of Boston, which was known as the Cambridge Agreement, after the university.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1650, Governor Thomas Dudley signed the charter creating the corporation that still governs Harvard College.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge grew slowly as an agricultural village eight miles (13 km) by road from Boston, the colony's capital.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] By the American Revolution, most residents lived near the Common and Harvard College, with most of the town comprising farms and estates.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] On January 24, 1776, Henry Knox arrived with an artillery train captured from Fort Ticonderoga, which allowed Washington to force the British Army to evacuate Boston.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Most of the Loyalist estates in Cambridge were confiscated after the Revolutionary War.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Between 1790 and 1840, Cambridge grew rapidly with the construction of West Boston Bridge in 1792 connecting Cambridge directly to Boston, making it no longer necessary to travel eight miles (13 km) through the Boston Neck, Roxbury, and Brookline to cross the Charles River.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] A second bridge, the Canal Bridge, opened in 1809 alongside the new Middlesex Canal.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The new bridges and roads made what were formerly estates and marshland into prime industrial and residential districts.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the mid-19th century, Cambridge was the center of a literary revolution.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It was home to some of the famous Fireside poets, named because their poems would often be read aloud by families in front of their evening fires.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Fireside poets, including Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, James Russell Lowell, and Oliver Wendell Holmes, were highly popular and influential in this era.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In addition, the town was connected to the Boston & Maine Railroad, leading to the development of Porter Square as well as the creation of neighboring Somerville from the formerly rural parts of Charlestown.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge was incorporated as a city in 1846.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city's commercial center began to shift from Harvard Square to Central Square, which became the city's downtown around that time.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] For much of the 19th and early 20th centuries, the city's largest employer was the New England Glass Company, founded in 1818.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, it was the world's largest and most modern glassworks.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1888, Edward Drummond Libbey moved all production to Toledo, Ohio, where it continues today under the name Owens-Illinois.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The company's flint glassware with heavy lead content is prized by antique glass collectors, and the Toledo Museum of Art has a large collection.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and the Sandwich Glass Museum on Cape Cod also house several pieces.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1895, Edwin Ginn, founder of Ginn and Company, built the Athenaeum Press Building for his publishing textbook empire.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] By 1920, Cambridge was one of New England's main industrial cities, with nearly 120,000 residents.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Among the largest businesses in Cambridge during the period of industrialization was Carter's Ink Company, whose neon sign long adorned the Charles River and which was for many years the world's largest ink manufacturer.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Welch (1927–1963, originator of Junior Mints, Sugar Daddies, Sugar Mamas, and Sugar Babies, now part of Tootsie Roll Industries).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Main Street was nicknamed "Confectioner's Row".
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Only the Cambridge Brands subsidiary of Tootsie Roll Industries remains in town, still manufacturing Junior Mints in the old Welch factory on Main Street.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Blake and Knowles Steam Pump Company (1886), the Kendall Boiler and Tank Company (1880, now in Chelmsford, Massachusetts), and the New England Glass Company (1818–1878) were among the industrial manufacturers in what are now Kendall Square and East Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1935, the Cambridge Housing Authority and the Public Works Administration demolished an integrated low-income tenement neighborhood with African Americans and European immigrants.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In its place, it built the whites-only "Newtowne Court" public housing development and the adjoining, blacks-only "Washington Elms" project in 1940; the city required segregation in its other public housing projects as well.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] As industry in New England began to decline during the Great Depression and after World War II, Cambridge lost much of its industrial base.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It also began to become an intellectual, rather than an industrial, center.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Harvard University, which had always been important as both a landowner and an institution, began to play a more dominant role in the city's life and culture.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] When Radcliffe College was established in 1879, the town became a mecca for some of the nation's most academically talented female students.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] MIT's move from Boston to Cambridge in 1916 reinforced Cambridge's status as an intellectual center of the United States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] After the 1950s, the city's population began to decline slowly as families tended to be replaced by single people and young couples.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In Cambridge Highlands, the technology company Bolt, Beranek, & Newman produced the first network router in 1969 and hosted the invention of computer-to-computer email in 1971.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The 1980s brought a wave of high technology startups.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Those selling advanced minicomputers were overtaken by the microcomputer.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge-based VisiCorp made the first spreadsheet software for personal computers, VisiCalc, and helped propel the Apple II to consumer success.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It was overtaken and purchased by Cambridge-based Lotus Development, maker of Lotus 1-2-3 (which was, in turn, replaced in by Microsoft Excel).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city continues to be home to many startups.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Kendall Square was a software hub through the dot-com boom and today hosts offices of such technology companies as Google, Microsoft, and Amazon.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Square also now houses the headquarters of Akamai.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1976, Harvard's plans to start experiments with recombinant DNA led to a three-month moratorium and a citizen review panel.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the end, Cambridge decided to allow such experiments but passed safety regulations in 1977.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] This led to regulatory certainty and acceptance when Biogen opened a lab in 1982, in contrast to the hostility that caused the Genetic Institute, a Harvard spinoff, to abandon Somerville and Boston for Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The biotech and pharmaceutical industries have since thrived in Cambridge, which now includes headquarters for Biogen and Genzyme; laboratories for Novartis, Teva, Takeda, Alnylam, Ironwood, Moderna Therapeutics, Editas Medicine; support companies such as Cytel; and many smaller companies.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] During the era of rent control in Massachusetts, at least 20 percent of all rent controlled apartments in Cambridge housed high-income earners, with the majority going to people with professional, technical, and managerial jobs.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In an independent study conducted of 2/3 of the rent controlled apartments in Cambridge in 1988, 246 were households headed by doctors, 298 by lawyers, 265 by architects, 259 by professors, and 220 by engineers.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] There were 2,650 with students, including 1,503 with graduate students.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The end of rent control in 1994 had numerous effects on the city.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Within four years of repealing the law, Cambridge, where "the city's form of rent control was unusually strict," saw new housing and construction increase by 50%, and the tax revenue from construction permits tripled.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Property values in Cambridge increased by about $7.8 billion in the decade following the repeal.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Roughly a quarter of this increase, $1.8 billion ($3 billion in 2024 dollars), was due to the repeal of rent control.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Close to 40% of all Cambridge properties were under rent control when it was repealed.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Their property values appreciated faster than non-rent controlled properties, as did the properties around them.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] By the end of the 20th century, Cambridge had one of the most costly housing markets in the Northeastern United States.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge's mix of amenities and proximity to Boston kept housing prices relatively stable despite the bursting of the United States housing bubble in 2008 and 2009.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge has been a sanctuary city since 1985 and reaffirmed its status as such in 2006.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Census Bureau, Cambridge has a total area of 7.1 square miles (18 km2), 6.4 square miles (17 km2) of which is land and 0.7 square miles (1.8 km2) (9.82%) of which is water.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The border between Cambridge and the neighboring city of Somerville passes through densely populated neighborhoods, which are connected by the MBTA Red Line.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Some of the main squares, Inman, Porter, and to a lesser extent, Harvard and Lechmere, are very close to the city line, as are Somerville's Union and Davis Squares.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Through the City of Cambridge's exclusive municipal water system, the city further controls two exclave areas, one being Payson Park Reservoir and Gatehouse, a 2009 listed American Water Landmark located roughly one mile west of Fresh Pond and surrounded by the town of Belmont.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The second area is the larger Hobbs Brook and Stony Brook watersheds, which share borders with neighboring towns and cities including Lexington, Lincoln, Waltham and Weston.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge has been called the "City of Squares", as most of its commercial districts are major street intersections known as squares.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Each square acts as a neighborhood center.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Kendall Square, formed by the junction of Broadway, Main Street, and Third Street, has been called "the most innovative square mile on the planet", owing to its high concentration of entrepreneurial start-ups and quality of innovation which have emerged in the vicinity of the square since 2010.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Technology Square is an office and laboratory building cluster in this neighborhood.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Just over the Longfellow Bridge from Boston, at the eastern end of the MIT campus, it is served by the Kendall/MIT station on the MBTA Red Line subway.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Most of Cambridge's large office towers are located in the Square.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Kendall Square houses some of the biggest technological companies of the world, including Google, Microsoft, Amazon, Meta, and Apple.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] A biotech industry has developed in this area.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Cambridge Innovation Center, a large co-working space, is in Kendall Square at 1 Broadway.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Cambridge Center office complex is in Kendall Square, and not at the actual center of Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The "One Kendall Square" complex is nearby, but not actually in Kendall Square.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Central Square is formed by the junction of Massachusetts Avenue, Prospect Street, and Western Avenue.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Containing a variety of ethnic restaurants, it was economically depressed as recently as the late 1990s; it underwent gentrification in recent years (in conjunction with the development of the nearby University Park at MIT), and continues to grow more costly.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is served by the Central Square stop on the MBTA Red Line subway.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Lafayette Square, formed by the junction of Massachusetts Avenue, Columbia Street, Sidney Street, and Main Street, is considered part of the Central Square area.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridgeport is south of Central Square, and bordered by MIT, the Charles River, Massachusetts Avenue, and River Street.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Harvard Square is formed by the junction of Massachusetts Avenue, Brattle Street, Dunster Street, and JFK Street.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] This is the primary site of Harvard University and a major Cambridge shopping area.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is served by the Harvard Square Red Line station.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Harvard Square was originally the Red Line's northwestern terminus and a major transfer point to streetcars that also operated in a short tunnel—which is still a major bus terminal, although the area under the Square was reconfigured dramatically in the 1980s when the Red Line was extended.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] A short distance away from the square lies the Cambridge Common, while the neighborhood north of Harvard and east of Massachusetts Avenue is known as Baldwin, in honor of the first Black principal of Cambridge public schools, Maria L.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It was renamed "Baldwin" in 2021, and so some know the area better by its former name, Agassiz, after the famed scientist Louis Agassiz.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Porter Square is about a mile north on Massachusetts Avenue from Harvard Square, at the junction of Massachusetts and Somerville Avenues.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It includes part of the city of Somerville and is served by the Porter Square Station, a complex housing a Red Line stop and a Fitchburg Line commuter rail stop.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Lesley University's University Hall and Porter campus are in Porter Square.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Inman Square is at the junction of Cambridge and Hampshire streets in mid-Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is home to restaurants, bars, music venues, and boutiques.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Victorian streetlights, benches, and bus stops were added to the streets in the 2000s, and a new city park was installed.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Lechmere Square is at the junction of Cambridge and First streets, adjacent to the CambridgeSide Galleria shopping mall.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is served by Lechmere station on the MBTA Green Line.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the Köppen-Geiger classification, Cambridge has a hot-summer humid continental climate (Dfa) with four well-defined seasons.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Summers are warm to hot, fall and spring are cool and rainy, and winter is cold and gray with occasional snowstorms.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Abundant rain falls on the city (and in the winter often as snow); it has no dry season.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The average January temperature is 26.6 °F (−3 °C), making Cambridge part of Group D, independent of the isotherm.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] As of the census of 2010, there were 105,162 people, 44,032 households, and 17,420 families residing in the city.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The population density was 16,354.9 inhabitants per square mile (6,314.7/km2).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] There were 47,291 housing units at an average density of 7,354.7 per square mile (2,839.7/km2).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 66.60% White, 11.70% Black or African American, 0.20% Native American, 15.10% Asian (3.7% Chinese, 1.4% Asian Indian, 1.2% Korean, 1.0% Japanese), 0.01% Pacific Islander, 2.10% from other races, and 4.30% from two or more races.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] 7.60% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race (1.6% Puerto Rican, 1.4% Mexican, 0.6% Dominican, 0.5% Colombian & Salvadoran, 0.4% Spaniard).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Non-Hispanic Whites were 62.1% of the population in 2010, down from 89.7% in 1970.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] An individual resident of Cambridge is known as a Cantabrigian.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 2010, there were 44,032 households, out of which 16.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 28.9% were married couples living together, 8.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 60.4% were non-families.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] 40.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The average household size was 2.00 and the average family size was 2.76.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the city, the population was spread out, with 13.3% of the population under the age of 18, 21.2% from 18 to 24, 38.6% from 25 to 44, 17.8% from 45 to 64, and 9.2% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] For every 100 females, there were 96.1 males.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.7 males.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $47,979, and the median income for a family was $59,423 (these figures had risen to $58,457 and $79,533 respectively as of a 2007 estimate).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Males had a median income of $43,825 versus $38,489 for females.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The per capita income for the city was $31,156.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] About 8.7% of families and 12.9% of the population were below the poverty line, including 15.1% of those under age 18 and 12.9% of those age 65 or over.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Locals living in and near the city jokingly refer to it as "The People's Republic of Cambridge".
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] For 2016, the residential property tax rate in Cambridge was $6.99 per $1,000.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge enjoys the highest possible bond credit rating, AAA, with all three Wall Street rating agencies.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 2000, 11.0% of city residents were of Irish ancestry; 7.2% were of English, 6.9% Italian, 5.5% West Indian and 5.3% German ancestry.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] 69.4% spoke only English at home, while 6.9% spoke Spanish, 3.2% Chinese or Mandarin, 3.0% Portuguese, 2.9% French Creole, 2.3% French, 1.5% Korean, and 1.0% Italian.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Data is from the 2009–2013 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Manufacturing was an important part of Cambridge's economy in the late 19th and early 20th century.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Since the late 20th century, Kendall Square and adjacent areas have shifted from primarily industrial uses toward biotechnology, laboratory, office, and mixed-use development.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] As a cradle of technological innovation, Cambridge was home to technology firms Analog Devices, Akamai, Bolt, Beranek, and Newman (BBN Technologies) (now part of Raytheon), General Radio (later GenRad), Lotus Development Corporation (now part of IBM), Polaroid, Symbolics, and Thinking Machines.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Little, and Lotus were Cambridge's top employers, with over 1,000 employees, but they faded out a few years later.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Health care and biotechnology firms such as Genzyme, Biogen Idec, bluebird bio, Millennium Pharmaceuticals, Sanofi, Pfizer and Novartis have significant presences in the city.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Though headquartered in Switzerland, Novartis continues to expand its operations in Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Other major biotech and pharmaceutical firms expanding their presence in Cambridge include GlaxoSmithKline, AstraZeneca, Shire, and Pfizer.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Most of Cambridge's biotech firms are in Kendall Square and East Cambridge, which decades ago were the city's center of manufacturing.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Some others are in University Park at MIT, a new development in another former manufacturing area.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] None of the high technology firms that once dominated the economy was among the 25 largest employers in 2005, but by 2008 Akamai and ITA Software were.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Google, IBM Research, Microsoft Research, and Philips Research maintain offices in Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In late January 2012—less than a year after acquiring Billerica-based analytic database management company, Vertica—Hewlett-Packard announced it would also be opening its first offices in Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Also around that time, e-commerce giants Staples and Amazon.com said they would be opening research and innovation centers in Kendall Square.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] And LabCentral provides a shared laboratory facility for approximately 25 emerging biotech companies.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The proximity of Cambridge's universities has also made the city a center for nonprofit groups and think tanks, including the National Bureau of Economic Research, the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory, the Lincoln Institute of Land Policy, Cultural Survival, and Science Club for Girls.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In September 2011, Cambridge launched its Entrepreneur Walk of Fame initiative, recognizing people who have made contributions to innovation in global business.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 2021, Cambridge was one of approximately 27 US cities to receive a AAA rating from each of the three major US credit rating agencies, Moody's Investors Service, Standard & Poor's and Fitch Ratings.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] 2021 marked the 22nd consecutive year that Cambridge had retained this distinction.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge's massive tax base has allowed it to keep residential taxes fairly low, and its budget is the second largest in the state despite being the fourth largest in population.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge has a large and varied collection of permanent public art, on both city property, managed by the Cambridge Arts Council, Community Art Center, and the Harvard and MIT campuses.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Temporary public artworks are displayed as part of the annual Cambridge River Festival on the banks of the Charles River during winter celebrations in Harvard and Central Squares and at Harvard University campus sites.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Experimental forms of public artistic and cultural expression include the Central Square World's Fair, the annual Somerville-based Honk!
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Festival, and If This House Could Talk, a neighborhood art and history event.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Street musicians and other performers entertain tourists and locals in Harvard Square during the warmer months.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The performances are coordinated through a public process that has been developed collaboratively by the performers, city administrators, private organizations and business groups.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Cambridge public library contains four Works Progress Administration murals completed in 1935 by Elizabeth Tracy Montminy: *Religion*, *Fine Arts*, *History of Books and Paper*, and *The Development of the Printing Press*.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Despite intensive urbanization during the late 19th century and the 20th century, Cambridge has several historic buildings, including some from the 17th century.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city also has abundant contemporary architecture, largely built by Harvard and MIT.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city has an active music scene, from classical performances to the latest popular bands.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Beyond its colleges and universities, Cambridge has many music venues, including The Middle East, Club Passim, The Plough and Stars, The Lizard Lounge and the Nameless Coffeehouse.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Consisting largely of densely built residential space, Cambridge lacks significant tracts of public parkland.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Easily accessible open space on the university campuses, including Harvard Yard, Radcliffe Yard, and MIT's Great Lawn, as well as the considerable open space of Mount Auburn Cemetery and Fresh Pond Reservation, partly compensates for this.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] At Cambridge's western edge, the cemetery is known as a garden cemetery because of its landscaping (the oldest planned landscape in the country) and arboretum.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Although known as a Cambridge landmark, much of the cemetery lies within Watertown.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is also an Important Bird Area (IBA) in the Greater Boston area.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Fresh Pond Reservation is the largest open green space in Cambridge with 162 acres (656,000 m2) of land around a 155-acre (627,000 m2) kettle hole lake.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] This land includes a 2.25-mile walking trail around the reservoir and a public nine-hole golf course.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Public parkland includes the esplanade along the Charles River, which mirrors its Boston counterpart, Cambridge Common, Danehy Park, and Alewife Brook Reservation.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge is split between Massachusetts's 5th and 7th U.S. congressional districts.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The 5th district seat is held by Democrat Katherine Clark, who replaced now-Senator Ed Markey in a 2013 special election; the 7th is represented by Democrat Ayanna Pressley, elected in 2018.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The state's senior United States senator is Democrat Elizabeth Warren, elected in 2012, who lives in Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The governor of Massachusetts is Democrat Maura Healey, elected in 2022.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city is represented in the Massachusetts Senate as a part of the 2nd Middlesex, Middlesex and Suffolk, and 1st Suffolk and Middlesex districts.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] From 1860 to 1880, Republicans Abraham Lincoln, Ulysses S.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Hayes, and James Garfield each won Cambridge, Grant doing so by margins of over 20 points in both of his campaigns.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Following that, from 1884 to 1892, Grover Cleveland won Cambridge in all three of his presidential campaigns, by less than ten points each time.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Then from 1896 to 1924, Cambridge became something of a swing city with a slight Republican lean.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Republican candidates carried the city in five of the eight presidential elections during that time, with five of the elections resulting in either a plurality or a margin of victory of fewer than ten points.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] In the last 23 presidential elections, dating back to the nomination of Al Smith in the 1928 presidential election, Democratic presidential candidates have won Cambridge with every Democratic nominee since Massachusetts native John F.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Kennedy in 1960 receiving at least 70% of the vote, except for Jimmy Carter in 1976 and 1980.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Since 1928, the only Republican nominee to come within ten points of carrying Cambridge is Dwight Eisenhower in his 1956 reelection bid.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge has consistently voted for left-wing causes, such as ranked-choice voting, marijuana legalization, and physician-assisted suicide.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge has a city government led by a mayor and a nine-member city council.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] There is also a six-member school committee that functions alongside the superintendent of public schools.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The councilors and school committee members are elected every two years using proportional representation.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The mayor is elected by the city councilors from among themselves and serves as the chair of city council meetings.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The mayor also sits on the school committee.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The mayor is not the city's chief executive.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Rather, the city manager, who is appointed by the city council, serves in that capacity.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Under the city's Plan E form of government, the city council does not have the power to appoint or remove city officials who are under the direction of the city manager.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city council and its members are also forbidden from giving orders to any subordinate of the city manager.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Yi-An Huang is the City Manager as of September 6, 2022, succeeding Owen O'Riordan (now the Deputy City Manager) who briefly served as the Acting City Manager after Louis DePasquale resigned on July 5, 2022, after six years in office.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge was a county seat of Middlesex County, along with Lowell, until the abolition of executive county government.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Though the county government was abolished in 1997, the county still exists as a geographical and political region.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The employees of Middlesex County courts, jails, registries, and other county agencies are now employed directly by the Commonwealth.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The county's registry of Deeds remain in Cambridge, but the Probate and Family Court, Superior Court, District Attorney's and Sheriff's offices have had their operations transferred roughly nine miles north to Woburn.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The local Third District Court has shifted operations to Medford.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The Middlesex County Jail & House of Correction was also relocated 25 miles north from Cambridge to Billerica in 2014.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] At least 258 of the world's total 962 Nobel Prize winners have at some point in their careers been affiliated with universities in Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Radcliffe College, a women's liberal arts college, was based in Cambridge from its 1879 founding until its assimilation into Harvard in 1999.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge College is named for Cambridge and was based in Cambridge until 2017, when it consolidated to a new headquarters in neighboring Boston.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The American Academy of Arts and Sciences, one of the nation's oldest learned societies founded in 1780, is based in Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city's schools constitute the Cambridge Public School District.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge has three district public high school programs, including Cambridge Rindge and Latin School.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] As part of the Metro Boston area, the city's primary network-affiliated television stations are WBTS-CD (NBC), WBZ-TV (CBS), WCVB-TV (ABC), and WFXT (Fox).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Boston's CW affiliate, WLVI, is licensed to Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] There are several additional local stations that are accessible over the air.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city also is served by WGBH-TV and WGBX-TV, which are PBS member stations, with WGBH being the flagship station of the statewide WGBH Educational Foundation network.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Several TV services provide different portions of Cambridge with cable, DSL, fiber and satellite TV broadcasts and Internet including AT&T U-verse/DIRECTV, Comcast/Xfinity, and DISH Network.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Due to close proximity with Somerville, local media frequently covers events and local topics of interest in both municipalities.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge is served by the online newspaper *Cambridge Day*, which was created in 2009 by Marc Levy.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] *Cambridge Day* became a nonprofit in 2024.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Levy left over differences of opinion and formed the *Cambridge Somerville Independent* in 2026.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The competing *Cambridge Chronicle* ceased publication in 2022 and today only cross-posts regional stories from other Gannett properties like Wicked Local.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Student-led newspapers of Harvard University, known respectively as The Harvard Crimson and The Harvard Independent, alongside The Tech of MIT, or the Register Forum of Cambridge Rindge & Latin High School also lightly feature local topics of interest as well.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] *The Boston Globe* publishes the "Camberville" section which covers Cambridge and Somerville.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Other hyperlocal online journalism such as Patch Media feature news about Cambridge as well.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The City of Cambridge's Public Library maintains a digital archive of many past local newspaper issues as part of its circulation.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge Community Television (CCTV) has served the city since its inception in 1988.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] CCTV operates Cambridge's public access television facility and three television channels, 8, 9, and 96, on the XFinity cable system (Comcast).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city has invited tenders from other cable providers, but Comcast remains its only fixed television and broadband utility, though services from American satellite TV providers are available.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge obtains water from Hobbs Brook (in Lincoln and Waltham) and Stony Brook (Waltham and Weston), as well as an emergency connection to the Massachusetts Water Resources Authority.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city owns over 1,200 acres (486 ha) of land in other towns that includes these reservoirs and portions of their watershed.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Water from these reservoirs flows by gravity through an aqueduct to Fresh Pond in Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] It is then treated in an adjacent plant and pumped uphill to an elevation of 176 feet (54 m) above sea level at the Payson Park Reservoir (Belmont).
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The water is then redistributed downhill via gravity to individual users in the city.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] A new water treatment plant opened in 2001.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] In October 2016, the city announced that, owing to drought conditions, they would begin buying water from the MWRA.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] On January 3, 2017, Cambridge announced that "As a result of continued rainfall each month since October 2016, we have been able to significantly reduce the need to use MWRA water.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge is served by several major roads, including MA 2, MA 3, MA 16, MA 28 and US 3.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The Massachusetts Turnpike does not pass through Cambridge but is accessible by an exit in nearby Allston.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Both US 1 and I-93 provide additional access at the eastern end of Cambridge via Leverett Circle in Boston.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] MA 2A runs the length of the city, chiefly along Massachusetts Avenue.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The Charles River forms the southern border of Cambridge and is crossed by 11 bridges connecting Cambridge to Boston, eight of which are open to motorized road traffic, including the Longfellow Bridge and the Harvard Bridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge has an irregular street network because many of the roads date from the colonial era.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Contrary to popular belief, the road system did not evolve from longstanding cow-paths.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Roads connected various village settlements with each other and nearby towns and were shaped by geographic features, most notably streams, hills, and swampy areas.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Today, the major "squares" are typically connected by long, mostly straight roads, such as Massachusetts Avenue between Harvard Square and Central Square or Hampshire Street between Kendall Square and Inman Square.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] On October 25, 2022, Cambridge City Council voted 8–1 to eliminate parking minimums from the city code, citing declining car ownership, with the aim of promoting housing construction.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge is served by the Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority, including Porter station on the regional Commuter Rail, Lechmere station on the Green Line, and Alewife, Porter, Harvard, Central, and Kendall Square/MIT stations on the Red Line.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Alewife station, the terminus of the Red Line, has a large multi-story parking garage.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The current elevated Lechmere station opened in March 2022 as part of the Green Line Extension.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The Harvard bus tunnel under Harvard Square connects to the Red Line underground.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] This tunnel was originally opened for streetcars in 1912 and served trackless trolleys, trolleybuses, and buses as the routes were converted; four lines of the MBTA trolleybus system continued to use it until their conversion to diesel in 2022.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The tunnel was partially reconfigured when the Red Line was extended to Alewife in the early 1980s.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Both Union Square station in Somerville on the Green Line and Community College station in Charlestown on the Orange Line are located just outside of Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Besides the state-owned transit agency, the city is also served by the Charles River Transportation Management Agency (CRTMA) shuttles which are supported by some of the largest companies operating in the city, in addition to the municipal government itself.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge has several bike paths, including one along the Charles River, and the Linear Park connecting the Minuteman Bikeway at Alewife with the Somerville Community Path.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] A connection to Watertown opened in 2022.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Bike parking is common and there are bike lanes on many streets, although concerns have been expressed regarding the suitability of many of the lanes.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] On several central MIT streets, bike lanes transfer onto the sidewalk.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge bans cycling on certain sections of sidewalk where pedestrian traffic is heavy.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Walking is a popular activity in Cambridge.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] In 2000, among U.S. cities with more than 100,000 residents, Cambridge had the highest percentage of commuters who walked to work.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge's major historic squares have changed into modern walking neighborhoods, including traffic calming features based on the needs of pedestrians rather than of motorists.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The Boston intercity bus and train stations at South Station in Boston, and Logan International Airport in East Boston, both of which are accessible by subway.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The Fitchburg Line rail service from Porter Square connects to some western suburbs.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Since October 2010, there has also been intercity bus service between Alewife Station (Cambridge) and New York City.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] In addition to the Cambridge Police Department, the city is patrolled by the Fifth (Brighton) Barracks of Troop H of the Massachusetts State Police.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Owing, however, to proximity, the city also practices functional cooperation with the Fourth (Boston) Barracks of Troop H, as well.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The campuses of Harvard and MIT are patrolled by the Harvard University Police Department and MIT Police Department, respectively.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city of Cambridge is protected by the Cambridge Fire Department.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Established in 1832, the CFD operates eight engine companies, four ladder companies, one rescue company, and three paramedic squad companies from eight fire stations located throughout the city.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city of Cambridge receives emergency medical services from PRO EMS, a privately contracted ambulance service.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Further educational services are provided at the Cambridge Public Library.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The large modern main building was built in 2009, and connects to the restored 1888 Richardson Romanesque building.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] It was founded as the private Cambridge Athenaeum in 1849 and was acquired by the city in 1858, and became the Dana Library.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The 1888 building was a donation of Frederick H.
[src:cambridge-massachusetts/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The library system also includes six neighborhood branches: Boudreau, Central Square, Collins, O’Connell, O’Neill, and Valente.
